	<li><div class="even">
	<p class="permlink"><a href="http://24ways.org/2008/contract-killer#c002156" id="c002156">23/12/2008</a></p>
	<h4><a href="http://www.websushi.co.uk"><img src="http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=939b38cdb44c99695f864dd2f90abeb9&amp;size=100&amp;default=http%3A%2F%2Fcloud.24ways.org%2Fimg%2Fgravatar.png" class="gravatar" alt="" height="100" width="100" /> Kevin Davies <small>http://www.websushi.co.uk</small></a></h4>
		<p>Great Article Andy.</p>

	<p>I&#8217;ve just gone through the process of having my contract reviewed by a law firm, as the template copy I had been using seemed to be woefully lacking in some areas.</p>

	<p>One important piece of advice the law firm gave me is to make sure my contract is the last documented agreement on the issue. If I raise a contract which is signed, and they then raise a purchase order for me to work to, it may be I&#8217;m legally obliged to work to my client&#8217;s terms rather than mine.</p>

	<p>Have a great Christmas (and Happy Birthday!).</p>

	<p>All the best,<br />
Kevin</p>


