	<p>— @andi farr got that right. It&#8217;s all part of the hard boiled theme.</p>

	<p>@Aaron Russell: &#8220;Is there a danger that an informal approach like this – whilst making the contract process easier-going for the majority of your clients – actually might leave you open to risk from the small minority of problem-clients?&#8221; </p>

	<p>— Not in my experience, but I&#8217;m no dick or flat-foot. As @drewm pointed out, you should always have your contracts looked over by your lawyer.</p>

	<p>@Kevin Davies: &#8220;One important piece of advice the law firm gave me is to make sure my contract is the last documented agreement on the issue. If I raise a contract which is signed, and they then raise a purchase order for me to work to, it may be I’m legally obliged to work to my client’s terms rather than mine.&#8221; </p>

